      "output": "Title: How do I upgrade to Windows 11 an a OMEN by HP Laptop 15-ce0... - HP Support Community - 9328149\nURL: https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Gaming-Notebooks/How-do-I-upgrade-to-Windows-11-an-a-OMEN-by-HP-Laptop-15/td-p/9328149\nPublished: 2025-03-01T17:32:23.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nYour PC's Intel 7th generation core processor does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 hardware requirements of an Intel 8th generation core or ...\n\n---\n\nTitle: Solved: Need to upgrade my Processor to support windows 11 - HP Support Community - 9355900\nURL: https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Hardware-and-Upgrade-Questions/Need-to-upgrade-my-Processor-to-support-windows-11/td-p/9355900\nPublished: 2025-03-30T11:25:37.000Z\nAuthor: Author\nHighlights:\nYou have a HP OMEN 15-ce004na notebook. Chapter 3 of the service manual indicates only 7th gen core processor motherboards were supported.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Solved: Windows 11 Upgrade on HP 15 - HP Support Community - 9333539\nURL: https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Hardware-and-Upgrade-Questions/Windows-11-Upgrade-on-HP-15/td-p/9333539\nPublished: 2025-03-07T02:44:30.000Z\nAuthor: Author\nHighlights:\nIs it worth it to upgrade my HP15 Intel Pentium N3540 Processor to Windows 11? If that is even possible.\n...\nYou can upgrade to W11, but you have to use a workaround because your notebook's processor does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 processor requirements of an Intel 8th generation core or newer processor.\n...\nIf you are happy with your PC, and if you are interested in doing an in-place upgrade from W10 > W11 24H2 on your PC as is, watch this video, which is the easiest way to do it in my opinion, and I have tried many different ways to do this during the last 3 years.\n...\nDownload the W24\n...\nISO file and use that (3rd option).\n...\nYou'll have to repeat this procedure each October when Microsoft rolls out the new builds because a PC that does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 hardware requirements will never automatically get the update to the next build.\n...\nOther than that, your PC will continue to get the monthly cumulative and other updates.\n...\nThat's only a minor inconvenience to have continued OS support beyond October of 2025.\n...\nIf the notebook does not work as well on W11 as it did on W10, you have 10 days to easily go back to W10 as long as you don't delete the W11 upgrade files or the Windows.old folder.\n...\nYou can upgrade to W11, but you have to use a workaround because your notebook's processor does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 processor requirements of an Intel 8th generation core or newer processor.\n...\nIf you are happy with your PC, and if you are interested in doing an in-place upgrade from W10 > W11 24H2 on your PC as is, watch this video, which is the easiest way to do it in my opinion, and I have tried many different ways to do this during the last 3 years.\n...\nDownload the W24H2 ISO file and use that (3rd option).\n...\nYou can download the free 7-Zip file utility from the link below. The top line is for 64 bit.\n...\nYou'll have to repeat this procedure each October when Microsoft rolls out the new builds because a PC that does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 hardware requirements will never automatically get the update to the next build.\n...\nOther than that, your PC will continue to get the monthly cumulative and other updates.\n...\nThat's only a minor inconvenience to have continued OS support beyond October of 2025.\n...\nIf the notebook does not work as well on W11 as it did on W10, you have 10 days to easily go back to W10 as long as you don't delete the W11 upgrade files or the Windows.old folder.\n...\nSee option 1 at\n...\nlink below for how to go back to\n...\n10:\n\n---\n\nTitle: HP PCs - Upgrading to Windows 11 using Windows Update\nURL: https://support.hp.com/us-en/document/ish_4764126-4764171-16?jumpid=in_r11839_us/en/WIN11_globalalert\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nHP PCs - Up\n...\nUse Windows Update to install Windows 11 on your computer that came with the Windows 10 operating system.\n...\n* Make sure that the computer is eligible for Windows 11 by checking the \"How do I know if my computer meets Windows 11 minimum system requirements?\" section in[HP PCs –Support for Windows 11](https://support.hp.com/us-en/document/ish_4300937-4295746-16). The Windows 11 upgrade option might not be available in Windows Update if your computer is not eligible for the upgrade.\n...\nconfigured with components that do not meet the minimum hardware requirements for Windows 11. HP recommends\n...\nfrom Microsoft to\n...\n* Specific versions of some models might have the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) disabled by request of the customer. These computers\nmight not have an option in the BIOS for TPM. HP recommends that you do not upgrade these models to the Windows 11 operating\nsystem.\n...\n## System requirements for installing Windows 11\n...\nMicrosoft requires that your computer hardware meets the following system requirements before you can install Windows 11.\n...\nspecifications).\n...\n|\n1 GHz or faster with two or more cores on a compatible 64-bit processor or system on a chip (SoC).\n...\nSee[Windows 11 supported\n...\nprocessors](https://docs.\n...\n.com/windows-hardware/design/minimum/supported/windows-11-supported-\n...\n-processors)or[Windows 11 supported AMD processors](https://docs.microsoft.com/windows-hardware/design/minimum/supported/windows-11-supported-amd-processors).\n...\nMemory (RAM)\n...\n4 GB or greater\n...\nGraphics card\n|\nCompatible with DirectX 12 or later, with a WDDM 2.0 driver\n|\n...\nHigh-definition display (720p), 9 in monitor (or greater), 8 bits per color channel\n...\nTPM\n|\nTrusted Platform Module (TPM) version 2.0\n|\n...\n, Secure Boot\n...\n64 GB (or greater)\n...\nWindows 11 Home edition requires an internet connection and a Microsoft account to complete device setup on\n...\n### Update software, drivers, and BIOS and enable Trusted Platform Module (TPM)\n...\nDownload and install the latest software and drivers and the latest version of the BIOS. If necessary, enable TPM.\n...\n2. Download and install the latest version of the BIOS for your computer. See one of\n...\nfor more information.\n...\n* Based on your location and the model of your computer, you might need to enable the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) to meet\nthe minimum system requirements.\n...\n1. Restart the computer, and then pressf10to openBIOS Setup Utility.\n...\n2. On theSecuritytab, check to see if theTPM Deviceoption isHidden.\n...\n3. Change theTPM Deviceoption toAvailable.\n4. Change theTPM Stateoption toEnabled.\n\n---\n\nTitle: I want to upgrade my windows 10 to windows 11, but my proces... - HP Support Community - 9351870\nURL: https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Hardware-and-Upgrade-Questions/I-want-to-upgrade-my-windows-10-to-windows-11-but-my/td-p/9351870\nPublished: 2025-03-26T07:52:25.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nProduct: HP Notebook - 15-da0352tu\n...\nOperating System: Microsoft Windows 10 (64-bit)\n...\nProcessor is Intel(R) Core(TM) i3-7020U CPU @ 2.30GHz 2.30 GHz\n...\nI'm planning to upgrade windows from 10 to 11 but my PC health check up says your processor is not compactable, please assist to fix this issue and please guide me how to upgrade to windows 11.\n...\nThe processor is an integral part of the motherboard and is not upgradable.\n...\nIf you are happy with your PC, and if you are interested in doing an in-place upgrade to W11 24H2 on your PC as is, watch this video, which is the easiest way to do it in my opinion, and I have tried many different ways to do this during the last 3 years.\n...\nDownload the W24H2 ISO file and use that (3rd option).\n...\nYou can download the free 7-Zip file utility from the link below. The top line is for 64 bit.\n...\nYou'll have to repeat this procedure each October when Microsoft rolls out the new builds because a PC that does not meet Microsoft's minimum W11 hardware requirements will never automatically get the update to the next build.\n...\nOther than that, your PC will continue to get the monthly cumulative and other updates.\n...\nThat's only a minor inconvenience to have continued OS support beyond October of 2025.\n...\nIf things don't work right on W11, you have 10 days to easily go back to W10 as long as you don't delete the W1 upgrade files or the Windows.old folder.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Why the Intel Core i5-7300HQ isn't a supported processor while it has enough power to run Windows 11? - Microsoft Q&A\nURL: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/586059/why-the-intel-core-i5-7300hq-isnt-a-supported-proc\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nMicrosoft minimal processor requierments are 1 gigahertz (GHz) or faster with 2 or more cores on a compatible 64-bit processor or System on a Chip (SoC). The Intel Core i5-7300HQ's specifications are: 2,50 GHz, 4 Cores 64-bits and SoC support. So then why it isn't a supported processor?\n...\nAlso Windows 11 can be installed in most computers in either a supported or unsupported fashion.\n...\nIt is not only about performance, but also because the security architecture of the processors. In this case most of pre-Gen8 Intel have been classified as \"Not Recommended\" or not supported, because of lack of Secure Boot or TPM compatibility.\n...\nYou can see other ways to install Windows 11, including the bypass of TPM check during the installation process: https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/ways-to-install-windows-11-e0edbbfb-cfc5-4011-868b-2ce77ac7c70e\n...\nAnd also general information about Microsoft statement on installing on not recommended devices: https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/installing-windows-11-on-devices-that-don-t-meet-minimum-system-requirements-0b2dc4a2-5933-4ad4-9c09-ef0a331518f1\n...\nBut, my laptop with a 7300-HQ has TPM 2.0 and i know that beacuse that requirement has a check sign on the pc health check app. Secure boot also works too i have uefi with secure boot and it works perfectly fine.\n...\nI have a laptop with i5 7300hq processor. I installed windows 11 by bypassing the TPM check. I thought my laptop wouldn't get updates but surprisingly I can receive and install updates.\n...\nDo you still recommend upgrading from W10 to W11 with that processor? I got the message today that in October W10 will no longer be supported, but the check app says my i5-7300HQ is not supported, even though it is SoC compatible and TPM 2.0 being enabled on the computer.\n...\nI have i acer nitro 5 an515-51 with i5-7300HQ , NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1050 Ti 16gb ram 1tb rocket q ssd i feel this is enough for windows 11 yet just 1 cpu gen behind it wont upgrade\n...\ni been told you can make a setup usb and bypass the check and install so going to try it on a spare 256gb ssd i got\n...\nThe Intel Core i5-7300HQ's specifications are: 2,50 GHz, 4 Cores 64-bits and SoC support. So then why it isn't a supported processor?\n...\nAccording to Microsoft:\n...\nDevices that do not meet the minimum system requirements had 52% more kernel mode crashes. Devices that do meet the minimum system requirements had a 99.8% crash free experience.\n...\nRead more here: https://blogs.windows.com/windows-insider/2021/08/27/update-on-windows-11-minimum-system-requirements-and-the-pc-health-check-app/\n...\nSo, if systems that met the minimum requirements were 99.8% crash free, and those that\n...\nhad 52% more\n...\nrequirements should have\n\n---\n\nTitle: Solved: win 11 upgrade issue - HP Support Community - 8934468\nURL: https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Operating-System-and-Recovery/win-11-upgrade-issue/td-p/8934468\nPublished: 2023-12-08T17:27:28.000Z\nAuthor: Author\nHighlights:\nDoes my notebook has tpm 2.0 to uprage my windows 10 to win 11 ?\n...\nYour notebook has a TPM 2.0 security device, there will be a security devices category in the device manager and the TPM 2.0 security device will be listed there.\n...\nIf you do not see such a setting, then check the security menu in the BIOS and see if you have to enable it.\n...\nIf no setting or the BIOS reports the TPM is enabled, then unfortunately, there isn't anything you can do other than to use a workaround to upgrade to W11.\n...\nthe W11 hardware requirements to W11 22H2.\n...\nYou have to use the version of the Rufus utility that I zipped up and attached in the discussion (v3.18).\n...\nIf the in-place upgrade fails, you should be able to clean install W11 using the bootable W11 installation flash drive you made with Rufus.\n...\nYour notebook has a TPM 2.0 security device, there will be a security devices category in the device manager and the TPM 2.0 security device will be listed there.\n...\nIf you do not see such a setting, then check the security menu in the BIOS and see if you have to enable it.\n...\nIf no setting or the BIOS reports the TPM is enabled, then unfortunately, there isn't anything you can do other than to use a workaround to upgrade to W11.\n...\nIf you are interested in installing W11 on your PC as is, you can read this discussion for how I upgraded several HP and Dell notebook and desktop PC's that did not meet the W11 hardware requirements to W11 22H2.\n...\nYou have to use the version of the Rufus utility that I zipped up and attached in the discussion (v3.18).\n...\nIf the in-place upgrade fails, you should be able to clean install W11 using the bootable W11 installation flash drive you made with Rufus.\n...\nThanks for your support Paul, TPM is active now and i can now install win 11. Bios settings worked.\n\n---\n\nTitle: HP PCs - Upgrading to Windows 11 using Windows Update\nURL: https://support.hp.com/gb-en/document/ish_4764126-4764171-16\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUse Windows Update to install Windows 11 on your computer that came with the Windows 10 operating system.\n...\n* Make sure that the computer is eligible for Windows 11 by checking the \"How do I know if my computer meets Windows 11 minimum system requirements?\" section in[HP PCs –Support for Windows 11](https://support.hp.com/gb-en/document/ish_4300937-4295746-16). The Windows 11 upgrade option might not be available in Windows Update if your computer is not eligible for the upgrade.\n...\n* Some computers might be configured with components that do not meet the minimum hardware requirements for Windows 11. HP recommends\n...\nthat you install[PC Health Check](https://aka.ms/GetPCHealthCheckApp)from Microsoft to determine if your computer is eligible.\n...\n* Devices that do not meet\n...\nminimum system requirements will remain on Windows\n...\n10 and\n...\n* Specific versions of some models might have the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) disabled by request of the customer. These computers\nmight not have an option in the BIOS for TPM. HP recommends that you do not upgrade these models to the Windows 11 operating\nsystem.\n...\n## System requirements for installing Windows 11\n...\nMicrosoft requires that your computer hardware meets the following system requirements before you can install Windows 11.\n...\n|\n1 GHz or faster with two or more cores on a compatible 64-bit processor or system on a chip (SoC).\n...\n-11-\n...\nor[Windows 11 supported AMD processors](https://docs.microsoft.com/windows-hardware/design/minimum/supported/windows-11-supported-amd-processors).\n...\nMemory (RAM)\n...\n4 GB or greater\n...\n|\nCompatible with DirectX 12 or later, with a WDDM 2.0 driver\n...\nHigh-definition display (72\n...\nin monitor (or greater), 8 bits per color channel\n...\nTPM\n|\nTrusted Platform Module (TPM) version 2.0\n|\n...\n, Secure Boot\n...\n64 GB (or greater) available storage\n...\nWindows 11 Home edition requires an internet connection and a Microsoft account to complete device setup on first use.\n...\n### Update software, drivers, and BIOS and enable Trusted Platform Module (TPM)\n...\nDownload and install the latest software and drivers and the latest version of the BIOS. If necessary, enable TPM.\n...\n* Based on your location and the model of your computer, you might need to enable the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) to meet\nthe minimum system requirements.\n...\n1. Restart the computer, and then pressf10to openBIOS Setup Utility.\n...\n2. On theSecuritytab, check to see if theTPM Deviceoption isHidden.\n...\n3. Change theTPM Deviceoption toAvailable.\n...\n4. Change theTPM Stateoption toEnabled.\n...\n## Install Windows 11 from Windows Update",
